choices.text:
always saying "no, please-don't hassle me" or "hey, chill out, please leave me alone". 

With my Asian parents, the lack of conversation and the constant harmony between them in hopes to please and avoid any conversation with them (esp with my siblings) is a killer.

The best we all can do is putting effort into having our needs and our voice heard (or introversion needs understood). There must be two ways: communicating to our parents our basic needs (one on one) and understanding through yoga or some exercise our personal strength (relationships are always unique) and thus reacting/interpreting/responding as according to the given situation. 

The main reason why people shy away from having a meaningful conversation is mainly because they fear for inconveniences (both parties interacting have something to hide) such as distraction, uncomfortable debriefings, emerging comments that can't be countered, etc. The ultimate result with this stagnant affair is futility and thus it might be considered better to self negotiate (via free time, actions seen as asocial, blocks of time for oneself, emotions, etc) or say nothing.

Another underlying dialogue/interactions problem for people in Asia are: 

1. Bigger focus on please or respect (yes your father can be mad, but feel he was respectful before the outburst or he stated his concern, but then maintain his worrisome individual attitude afterward, etc).
